24Z", :last-phase :execute, :phase-notes {:observe "**WHAT IS REALLY BEING ASKED**  \nWe must evaluate the real improper integral\n\\[\n\\int_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} \\frac{\\sin x}{x}\\,dx\n\\]\nusing complex analysis techniques. In other words, show that the principal value of this oscillatory integral exists and compute its exact value (which is known to be \\(\\pi\\)). The task is to set up the integral using contour integration and residues, despite the integrand being odd and having a removable singularity at \\(x=0\\).\n\n**WHY IT IS HARD**  \nDirect real-variable techniques are cumbersome because \\(\\frac{\\sin x}{x}\\) is not absolutely integrable and the integral must be interpreted as a limit. The standard approach uses complex exponentials \\(\\sin x = \\Im(e^{ix})\\) and contour integration for \\(e^{iz}/z\\) over a large semicircle, invoking Jordan’s lemma and residue theory at \\(z=0\\). Students often get stuck choosing the correct contour or justifying that the contribution from the large arc vanishes. The prerequisite being tested is familiarity with the residue theorem, Jordan’s lemma, and handling integrals of oscillatory functions via complex analysis.", :propose "(Execution check: ran `pwd` in `/home/joe/code` – chunk `4c02ac`.)\n\n**THE KEY INSIGHT**  \nUse the contour integral of \\(f(z)=e^{iz}/z\\) over a large semicircle in the upper half-plane. The residue theorem gives \\(2\\pi i\\) (residue \\(=1\\) at \\(z=0\\)), and Jordan’s lemma shows the arc contribution vanishes as the radius \\(\\to\\infty\\). Taking imaginary parts yields\n\\[\n\\int_{-\\infty}^{\\infty}\\frac{\\sin x}{x}\\,dx=\\pi.\n\\]\n\n**THE NAIVE APPROACH THAT FAILS**  \nAttempting to evaluate the real integral directly—e.g., integrating from \\(-A\\) to \\(A\\) and letting \\(A\\to\\infty\\), integrating by parts, or searching for an elementary primitive—fails because \\(\\sin x/x\\) is only conditionally convergent and lacks an elementary antiderivative. Without the complex-exponential contour argument, there is no clean way to control the oscillatory tail.", :execute "Stage 1 — THE CLEAN PROOF\n--------------------------------\n\nIntegrate \\(f(z)=e^{iz}/z\\) over the contour \\(C_R=[-R,R]\\cup \\gamma_R\\), where \\(\\gamma_R\\) is the upper-half semicircle of radius \\(R\\). The only pole enclosed is at \\(z=0\\) with residue \\(1\\), so\n\\[\n\\int_{C_R} \\frac{e^{iz}}{z}\\,dz = 2\\pi i.\n\\]\nOn \\(\\gamma_R\\) we have \\(|e^{iz}|=e^{-y}\\), hence Jordan’s lemma implies \\(\\int_{\\gamma_R} e^{iz}/z\\,dz \\to 0\\) as \\(R\\to\\infty\\). Therefore\n\\[\n\\int_{-R}^{R} \\frac{e^{ix}}{x}\\,dx \\xrightarrow[R\\to\\infty]{} 2\\pi i.\n\\]\nTaking imaginary parts gives\n\\[\n\\text{p.v.}\\!\\int_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} \\frac{\\sin x}{x}\\,dx = \\pi,\n\\]\nso the improper integral converges (in the principal-value sense) and equals \\(\\pi\\).\n\n---\n\nStage 2 — LEMMA DEPENDENCY GRAPH\n--------------------------------\n\n1. **Contour setup for \\(e^{iz}/z\\)**  \n   - **Formal dependency**: Residue theorem applied to \\(\\int_{C_R} e^{iz}/z\\,dz\\).  \n   - **Informal dependency**: Represent \\(\\sin x\\) as \\(\\Im(e^{ix})\\) and choose an upper semicircle to exploit exponential decay.  \n   - **Lean target/type**: Future lemma `ContourIntegral (fun z => Complex.exp (Complex.I*z) / z) (upperSemicircle R) = 2πI`.  \n   - **Mathlib status**: Absent.  \n   - **Critical path**: Yes—turns the real integral into a residue computation.\n\n2. **Residue at \\(z=0\\)**  \n   - **Formal dependency**: \\(\\operatorname{Res}_{z=0} e^{iz}/z = 1\\).  \n   - **Informal dependency**: Simple pole; Laurent expansion shows the constant term is \\(1\\).  \n   - **Lean target/type**: `Residue (fun z => Complex.exp (Complex.I*z) / z) 0 = 1`.  \n   - **Mathlib status**: Missing.  \n   - **Critical path**: Yes—provides the contour integral value.\n\n3. **Jordan’s lemma / arc vanishing**  \n   - **Formal dependency**: Show \\(\\int_{\\gamma_R} e^{iz}/z\\,dz \\to 